

( The inverse of matrix A is a of order n whose products with A is Identity matrix.
i.e. AA-1= I  ; I is Identity matrix of order n )
Q1
> X=matrix(c(2,4,5,7,9,11,1,3,6,2,-1,2,4,8,10,2,9,-2,1,3,3,6,-1,2,4),nrow=5,byrow=T)
> X
     [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4] [,5]
[1,]    2    4    5    7    9
[2,]   11    1    3    6    2
[3,]   -1    2    4    8   10
[4,]    2    9   -2    1    3
[5,]    3    6   -1    2    4
> det(X)
[1] -2582
Determenent of X is nonsingular.Therefore X inverse exist.
### By Adjoint Method ###
>cofact=matrix(nrow=5,ncol=5)
> for(i in 1:5)
+ for(j in 1:5)
+ {
+ cofact[i,j]=(-1)^(i+j)*det(X[-i,-j])
+ }
> cofact
